91, 39 thousand</li>\n<li>Rises gradually to 1901, 41 thousand</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The Montr&eacute;al line:<br/>\n<ul>\n<li>Begins at 1871, 107 thousand</li>\n<li>Rises gradually to 1881, 141 thousand&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Rises sharply to 1891, 217 thousand</li>\n<li>Rises sharply to 1901, 268 thousand</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The Qu&eacute;bec City line:<br/>\n<ul>\n<li>Begins at 1871, 60 thousand</li>\n<li>Rises gradually to 1881, 62 thousand&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Rises gradually to 1891, 63 thousand</li>\n<li>Rises gradually to 1901, 69 thousand</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The Toronto line:<br/>\n<ul>\n<li>Begins at 1871, 56 thousand</li>\n<li>Rises gradually to 1881, 86 thousand&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Rises sharply to 1891, 181 thousand</li>\n<li>Rises gradually to 1901, 208 thousand</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The first national census in Canada was conducted in <span data-ssml-say-as=\"date\">1871</span>. The graph shows the population sizes of some of the largest Canadian cities from each of the first four national censuses, which occurred every ten years.</p>",
